  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">COVID-19: Building Resilience through WASH, Sustainable Agriculture and Food and Income Security</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Due to the global outbreak of COVID-19 and with cases already reported in Sierra Leone, this grant was re-purposed in order to respond to the growing needs of the local community and to prevent any community transmission to the Health Clinic operated by the Handmaid Sisters. The funds will be used to procure hygiene promotion materials (buckets, soap, cleaning liquids among others) for both the clinic and surrounding communities and provide the necessary protective equipment for clinic staff (face masks, rubber boots, thermometers, goggles, hand gloves etc). 


CAFOD will also support the Handmaid Sisters to complete the construction of hand-dug wells in order to support the WASH needs of local communities; ensuring that proper prevention methods can continue through access to clean water for hand-washing. Recognizing the economic impact that lock-downs and travel restrictions will have on an already fragile economy, this project will also work to support local communities through agricultural training on post harvest losses, and provide inputs in the form of tools, seeds, small ruminants and goats. The Handmaid Sisters will also seek to improve the economic resilience of women and vulnerable individuals through a micro-loan scheme.</narrative>
  </description>
